p>We did it! &nbsp;Firefly is built and pushed out to the <a href=3D"http:/=
/ceph.com/">ceph.com</a> repositories.</p><p>This release will form the bas=
is for our long-term supported release Firefly, v0.80.x. The big new featur=
es are support for erasure coding and cache tiering, although a broad range=
 of other features, fixes, and improvements have been made across the code =
base. Highlights include:</p><ul><li><em>Erasure coding</em>: support for a=
 broad range of erasure codes for lower storage overhead and better data du=
rability.</li><li><em>Cache tiering</em>: support for creating =E2=80=98cac=
he pools=E2=80=99 that store hot, recently accessed objects with automatic =
demotion of colder data to a base tier. Typically the cache pool is backed =
by faster storage devices like SSDs.</li><li><em>Primary affinity</em>: Cep=
h now has the ability to skew selection of OSDs as the =E2=80=9Cprimary=E2=
=80=9D copy, which allows the read workload to be cheaply skewed away from =
parts of the cluster without migrating any data.</li><li><em>Key/value OSD =
backend</em>&nbsp;(experimental): An alternative storage backend for Ceph O=
SD processes that puts all data in a key/value database like leveldb. This =
provides better performance for workloads dominated by key/value operations=
 (like radosgw bucket indices).</li><li><em>Standalone radosgw</em>&nbsp;(e=
xperimental): The radosgw process can now run in a standalone mode without =
an apache (or similar) web server or fastcgi. This simplifies deployment an=
d can improve performance.</li></ul><p>We expect to maintain a series of st=
able releases based on v0.80 Firefly for as much as a year. In the meantime=
, development of Ceph continues with the next release, Giant, which will fe=
ature work on the CephFS distributed file system, more alternative storage =
backends (like RocksDB and f2fs), RDMA support, support for pyramid erasure=
 codes, and additional functionality in the block device (RBD) like copy-on=
-read and multisite mirroring.</p><p>This release is the culmination of a h=
uge collective effort by about 100 differrent contributors. &nbsp;Thank you=
 to everyone who has helped to make this release possible!</p><h3 id=3D"upg=
rade-sequencing">UPGRADE SEQUENCING <a class=3D"link-anchor" href=3D"https:=
//ceph.com/en/news/blog/2014/v0-80-firefly-released/#upgrade-sequencing">=
=C2=B6</a></h3><ul><li><p>If your existing cluster is running a version old=
er than v0.67 Dumpling, please first upgrade to the latest Dumpling release=
 before upgrading to v0.80 Firefly. Please refer to the_Dumpling upgrade_&n=
bsp;documentation.</p></li><li><p>We recommand adding the following to the =
[mon] section of your ceph.conf prior to upgrade:</p><blockquote><p>mon war=
n on legacy crush tunables =3D false</p></blockquote><p>This will prevent h=
ealth warnings due to the use of legacy CRUSH placement. Although it is pos=
sible to rebalance existing data across your cluster (see the upgrade notes=
 below), we do not normally recommend it for production environments as a l=
arge amount of data will move and there is a significant performance impact=
 from the rebalancing.</p></li><li><p>Upgrade daemons in the following orde=
r:</p><blockquote><ol><li>Monitors</li><li>OSDs</li><li>MDSs and/or radosgw=
</li></ol></blockquote><p>If the ceph-mds daemon is restarted first, it wil=
l wait until all OSDs have been upgraded before finishing its startup seque=
nce. If the ceph-mon daemons are not restarted prior to the ceph-osd daemon=
s, they will not correctly register their new capabilities with the cluster=
 and new features may not be usable until they are restarted a second time.=
</p></li><li><p>Upgrade radosgw daemons together. There is a subtle change =
in behavior for multipart uploads that prevents a multipart request that wa=
s initiated with a new radosgw from being completed by an old radosgw.</p><=
/li></ul><p><strong>UPGRADING FROM V0.79</strong></p><ul><li>OSDMap=E2=80=
=99s json-formatted dump changed for keys =E2=80=98full=E2=80=99 and =E2=80=
=98nearfull=E2=80=99. What was previously being outputted as =E2=80=98true=
=E2=80=99 or =E2=80=98false=E2=80=99 strings are now being outputted =E2=80=
=98true=E2=80=99 and =E2=80=98false=E2=80=99 booleans according to json syn=
tax.</li><li>HEALTH_WARN on =E2=80=98mon osd down out interval =3D=3D 0=E2=
=80=99. Having this option set to zero on the leader acts much like having =
the =E2=80=98noout=E2=80=99 flag set. This warning will only be reported if=
 the monitor getting the =E2=80=98health=E2=80=99 or =E2=80=98status=E2=80=
=99 request has this option set to zero.</li><li>Monitor =E2=80=98auth=E2=
=80=99 commands now require the mon =E2=80=98x=E2=80=99 capability. This ma=
tches dumpling v0.67.x and earlier, but differs from emperor v0.72.x.</li><=
li>A librados WATCH operation on a non-existent object now returns ENOENT; =
previously it did not.</li><li>Librados interface change: As there are no p=
artial writes, the rados_write() and rados_append() operations now return 0=
 on success like rados_write_full() always has. This includes the C++ inter=
face equivalents and AIO return values for the aio variants.</li></ul><h3 i=
d=3D"upgrading-from-v0.72-emperor">UPGRADING FROM V0.72 EMPEROR <a class=3D=
"link-anchor" href=3D"https://ceph.com/en/news/blog/2014/v0-80-firefly-rele=
ased/#upgrading-from-v0.72-emperor">=C2=B6</a></h3><ul><li>See notes above.=
</li><li>The =E2=80=98ceph -s=E2=80=99 or =E2=80=98ceph status=E2=80=99 com=
mand=E2=80=99s =E2=80=98num_in_osds=E2=80=99 field in the JSON and XML outp=
ut has been changed from a string to an int.</li><li>The recently added =E2=
=80=98ceph mds set allow_new_snaps=E2=80=99 command=E2=80=99s syntax has ch=
anged slightly; it is now =E2=80=98ceph mds set allow_new_snaps true=E2=80=
=99. The =E2=80=98unset=E2=80=99 command has been removed; instead, set the=
 value to =E2=80=98false=E2=80=99.</li><li>The syntax for allowing snapshot=
s is now =E2=80=98mds set allow_new_snaps &lt;true|false&gt;=E2=80=99 inste=
ad of =E2=80=98mds &lt;set,unset&gt; allow_new_snaps=E2=80=99.</li><li>=E2=
=80=98rbd ls=E2=80=99 on a pool which never held rbd images now exits with =
code 0. It outputs nothing in plain format, or an empty list in non-plain f=
ormat. This is consistent with the behavior for a pool which used to hold i=
mages, but contains none. Scripts relying on this behavior should be update=
d.</li><li>The MDS requires a new OSD operation TMAP2OMAP, added in this re=
lease. When upgrading, be sure to upgrade and restart the ceph-osd daemons =
before the ceph-mds daemon. The MDS will refuse to start if any up OSDs do =
not support the new feature.</li><li>The =E2=80=98ceph mds set_max_mds N=E2=
=80=99 command is now deprecated in favor of =E2=80=98ceph mds set max_mds =
N=E2=80=99.</li><li>The =E2=80=98osd pool create ...=E2=80=99 syntax has ch=
anged for erasure pools.</li><li>The default CRUSH rules and layouts are no=
w using the latest and greatest tunables and defaults. Clusters using the o=
ld values will now present with a health WARN state. This can be disabled b=
y adding =E2=80=98mon warn on legacy crush tunables =3D false=E2=80=99 to c=
eph.conf.</li><li>We now default to the =E2=80=98bobtail=E2=80=99 CRUSH tun=
able values that are first supported by Ceph clients in bobtail (v0.56) and=
 Linux kernel version v3.9. If you plan to access a newly created Ceph clus=
ter with an older kernel client, you should use =E2=80=98ceph osd crush tun=
ables legacy=E2=80=99 to switch back to the legacy behavior. Note that maki=
ng that change will likely result in some data movement in the system, so a=
djust the setting before populating the new cluster with data.</li><li>We n=
ow set the HASHPSPOOL flag on newly created pools (and new clusters) by def=
ault. Support for this flag first appeared in v0.64; v0.67 Dumpling is the =
first major release that supports it. It is first supported by the Linux ke=
rnel version v3.9. If you plan to access a newly created Ceph cluster with =
an older kernel or clients (e.g, librados, librbd) from a pre-dumpling Ceph=
 release, you should add =E2=80=98osd pool default flag hashpspool =3D fals=
e=E2=80=99 to the =E2=80=98[global]=E2=80=99 section of your =E2=80=98ceph.=
conf=E2=80=99 prior to creating your monitors (e.g., after =E2=80=98ceph-de=
ploy new=E2=80=99 but before =E2=80=98ceph-deploy mon create ...=E2=80=99).=
</li><li>The configuration option =E2=80=98osd pool default crush rule=E2=
